<row rowsep="1">
<entry>
<para><indexterm>
<primary>id attribute</primary>
<secondary>http-listener element</secondary>
</indexterm><literal>id</literal></para></entry>
<entry>
<para>none</para></entry>
<entry>
<para>The unique listener name. An <literal>http-listener</literal> name cannot begin
with a number.</para></entry>
</row>
<row>
<entry>
<para><indexterm>
<primary>address attribute</primary>
</indexterm><literal>address</literal></para></entry>
<entry>
<para>none</para></entry>
<entry>
<para>IP address of the listener. Can be in dotted-pair or IPv6 notation. Can be  <literal>
any</literal> (for <literal>INADDR_ANY</literal>) to listen on all IP addresses. Can
be a hostname.</para></entry>
</row>
<row>
<entry>
<para><indexterm>
<primary>port attribute</primary>
</indexterm><literal>port</literal></para></entry>
<entry>
<para>none</para></entry>
<entry>
<para>Port number on which the listener listens. Legal values are <literal>1</literal> -
 <literal>65535</literal>. On UNIX, creating sockets that listen on ports <literal>
1</literal> -  <literal>1024</literal> requires superuser privileges. Configuring
an SSL listener to listen on port 443 is standard.</para></entry>
</row><![ %Enterprise; [<row>
<entry>
<para><indexterm>
<primary>external-port attribute</primary>
</indexterm><literal>external-port</literal></para></entry>
<entry>
<para>none</para></entry>
<entry>
<para>(optional) Specifies the external port on which the connection is made.</para>
</entry>
</row><row>
<entry>
<para><indexterm>
<primary>family attribute</primary>
</indexterm><literal>family</literal></para></entry>
<entry></entry>
<entry>
<para>(optional) Deprecated. Do not use.</para></entry>
</row><row>
<entry>
<para><indexterm>
<primary>blocking-enabled attribute</primary>
</indexterm><literal>blocking-enabled</literal></para></entry>
<entry></entry>
<entry>
