<row>
<entry>
<para>Attribute</para></entry>
<entry>
<para>Default</para></entry>
<entry>
<para>Description</para></entry>
</row>
</thead>
<tbody>
<row rowsep="1">
<entry>
<para><indexterm>
<primary>name attribute</primary>
<secondary>jdbc-connection-pool element</secondary>
</indexterm><literal>name</literal></para></entry>
<entry>
<para>none</para></entry>
<entry>
<para>Specifies the name of the connection pool. A <olink targetptr="abhcz">jdbc-resource
</olink> element&rsquo;s <literal>pool-name</literal> attribute refers to this  <literal>
name</literal>.</para></entry>
</row>
<row>
<entry>
<para><indexterm>
<primary>datasource-classname attribute</primary>
</indexterm> <literal>datasource-<?SolBook preflinebreak>classname</literal></para>
</entry>
<entry>
<para>none</para></entry>
<entry>
<para>Specifies the class name of the associated vendor-supplied data source. This
class must implement <literal>java.sql.DataSource</literal>, <literal>java.sql.XADataSource
</literal> , <literal>javax.sql.<?SolBook preflinebreak>ConnectionPoolDatasource</literal>,
or a combination.</para></entry>
</row>
<row>
<entry>
<para><indexterm>
<primary>res-type attribute</primary>
</indexterm><literal>res-type</literal></para></entry>
<entry>
<para><literal>javax.sql.<?SolBook preflinebreak>DataSource</literal></para></entry>
<entry>
<para>(optional) Specifies the interface the data source class implements. The value
of this attribute can be <literal>javax.sql.DataSource</literal>, <literal>javax.sql.XADataSource
</literal> , or <literal>javax.sql.<?SolBook preflinebreak>ConnectionPoolDatasource
</literal>. If the value is not one of these interfaces, the default is used. An error
occurs if this attribute has a legal value and the indicated interface is not implemented
by the data source class.</para></entry>
</row>
<row>
<entry>
<para><indexterm>
<primary>steady-pool-size attribute</primary>
</indexterm> <literal>steady-pool-size</literal></para></entry>
<entry>
<para><literal>8</literal></para></entry>
<entry>
<para>(optional) Specifies the initial and minimum number of connections maintained
in the pool.</para></entry>
</row>
<row>
<entry>
<para><indexterm>
<primary>max-pool-size attribute</primary>
</indexterm><literal>max-pool-size</literal></para></entry>
<entry>
<para><literal>32</literal></para></entry>
<entry>
<para>(optional) Specifies the maximum number of connections that can be created to
satisfy client requests.</para></entry>
</row>
<row>
<entry>
<para><indexterm>
<primary>max-wait-time-in-millis attribute</primary>
</indexterm> <literal>max-wait-time-<?SolBook preflinebreak>in-millis</literal></para>
</entry>
<entry>
<para><literal>60000</literal></para></entry>
<entry>
<para>(optional) Specifies the amount of time, in milliseconds, that the caller is
willing to wait for a connection. If <literal>0</literal>, the caller is blocked indefinitely
until a resource is available or an error occurs.</para></entry>
</row>
<row>
<entry>
<para><indexterm>
<primary>pool-resize-quantity attribute</primary>
</indexterm> <literal>pool-resize-<?SolBook preflinebreak>quantity</literal></para>
</entry>
<entry>
<para><literal>2</literal></para></entry>
<entry>
<para>(optional) Specifies the number of connections to be destroyed if the existing
number of connections is above the <literal>steady-pool-size</literal> (subject to
the <literal>max-pool-size</literal> limit).</para>
<para>This is enforced periodically at the <literal>idle-time-out-in-seconds</literal> interval.
An idle connection is one that has not been used for a period of <literal>idle-time-out-in-seconds
</literal> .</para></entry>
</row>
<row>
<entry>
<para><indexterm>
<primary>idle-timeout-in-seconds attribute</primary>
</indexterm> <literal>idle-timeout-<?SolBook preflinebreak>in-seconds</literal></para>
</entry>
<entry>
<para><literal>300</literal></para></entry>
<entry>
<para>(optional) Specifies the maximum time that a connection can remain idle in the
pool. After this amount of time, the pool can close this connection.</para></entry>
</row>
<row>
<entry>
<para><indexterm>
<primary>transaction-isolation-level attribute</primary>
</indexterm> <literal>transaction-<?SolBook preflinebreak>isolation-level</literal></para>
</entry>
<entry>
<para>default JDBC driver isolation level</para></entry>
<entry>
<para>(optional) Specifies the transaction isolation level on the pooled database
connections. Allowed values are <literal>read-uncommitted</literal>, <literal>read-committed
</literal> , <literal>repeatable-read</literal>, or <literal>serializable</literal>.
</para>
<para>Applications that change the isolation level on a pooled connection programmatically
risk polluting the pool, which can lead to errors. See <literal>is-isolation-<?SolBook preflinebreak>level-<?SolBook preflinebreak>guaranteed
</literal>  for more details.</para></entry>
</row>
<row>
<entry>
<para><indexterm>
<primary>is-isolation-level-guaranteed attribute</primary>
</indexterm> <literal>is-isolation-<?SolBook preflinebreak>level-guaranteed</literal></para>
</entry>
<entry>
<para><literal>true</literal></para></entry>
<entry>
<para>(optional) Applicable only when <literal>transaction-<?SolBook preflinebreak>isolation-<?SolBook preflinebreak>level
</literal> is explicitly set. If <literal>true</literal>, every connection obtained
from the pool is guaranteed to have the desired isolation level. This might impact
performance on some JDBC drivers. Only set this attribute to <literal>false</literal> if
you are certain that the hosted applications do not return connections with altered
isolation levels.</para></entry>
</row>
<row>
<entry>
<para><indexterm>
<primary>is-connection-validation-required attribute</primary>
</indexterm> <literal>is-connection-<?SolBook preflinebreak>validation-<?SolBook preflinebreak>required
</literal></para></entry>
<entry>
<para><literal>false</literal></para></entry>
<entry>
<para>(optional) Specifies whether connections have to be validated before being given
to the application. If a resource&rsquo;s validation fails, it is destroyed, and a
new resource is created and returned.</para></entry>
</row>
<row>
<entry>
<para><indexterm>
<primary>connection-validation-method attribute</primary>
</indexterm> <literal>connection-<?SolBook preflinebreak>validation-<?SolBook preflinebreak>method
</literal></para></entry>
<entry>
<para><literal>auto-commit</literal></para></entry>
<entry>
<para>(optional) Legal values are as follows:</para>
<itemizedlist>
<listitem><para><literal>auto-commit</literal> (default), which uses <literal>Connection.<?SolBook preflinebreak>setAutoCommit<?SolBook preflinebreak>(Connection.<?SolBook preflinebreak>getAutoCommit())
</literal></para></listitem>
<listitem><para><literal>meta-data</literal>, which uses <literal>Connection.getMetaData()
</literal></para></listitem>
<listitem><para><literal>table</literal>, which performs a query on a table specified
in the <literal>validation-table-name</literal> attribute</para></listitem>
</itemizedlist>
</entry>
</row>
<row>
<entry>
<para><indexterm>
<primary>validation-table-name attribute</primary>
</indexterm> <literal>validation-<?SolBook preflinebreak>table-<?SolBook preflinebreak>name
</literal></para></entry>
<entry>
<para>none</para></entry>
<entry>
<para>(optional) Specifies the table name to be used to perform a query to validate
a connection. This parameter is mandatory if and only if <literal>connection-<?SolBook preflinebreak>validation-<?SolBook preflinebreak>method
</literal>  is set to <literal>table</literal>.</para></entry>
</row>
<row>
<entry>
<para><indexterm>
<primary>fail-all-connections attribute</primary>
</indexterm> <literal>fail-all-<?SolBook preflinebreak>connections</literal></para>
</entry>
<entry>
<para><literal>false</literal></para></entry>
<entry>
<para>(optional) If <literal>true</literal>, closes all connections in the pool if
a single validation check fails. This parameter is mandatory if and only if  <literal>
is-connection-<?SolBook preflinebreak>validation-<?SolBook preflinebreak>required
</literal> is set to <literal>true</literal>.</para></entry>
</row>
<row>
<entry>
<para><indexterm>
<primary>non-transactional-connections attribute</primary>
</indexterm> <literal>non-transactional-<?SolBook preflinebreak>connections</literal></para>
</entry>
<entry>
<para><literal>false</literal></para></entry>
<entry>
<para>(optional) If <literal>true</literal>, non-transactional connections can be
made to the JDBC connection pool. These connections are not automatically enlisted
with the transaction manager.</para></entry>
</row>
<row>
<entry>
<para><indexterm>
<primary>allow-non-component-callers attribute</primary>
</indexterm> <literal>allow-non-<?SolBook preflinebreak>component-<?SolBook preflinebreak>callers
</literal></para></entry>
<entry>
<para><literal>false</literal></para></entry>
<entry>
<para>(optional) If <literal>true</literal>, non-Java-EE components, such as servlet
filters, lifecycle modules, and third party persistence managers, can use this JDBC
connection pool. The returned connection is automatically enlisted with the transaction
context obtained from the transaction manager. Standard Java EE components can also
use such pools. Connections obtained by non-component callers are not automatically
closed at the end of a transaction by the container. They must be explicitly closed
by the caller.</para></entry>
</row>
</tbody>
</tgroup>
</table>
