<sect3><title>Properties</title>
<para>Most JDBC 3.0 drivers allow use of standard property lists to specify the user,
password, and other resource configuration information. Although properties are optional
with respect to the &ProductName;, some properties might be necessary for most databases.
For details, see the JDBC 3.0 Standard Extension API.</para>
<para>When properties are specified, they are passed to the vendor&rsquo;s data source
class (specified by the <literal>datasource-classname</literal> attribute) as is using
set<replaceable>Name</replaceable>(<replaceable>value</replaceable>) methods.</para>
<para>The <literal>user</literal> and <literal>password</literal> properties are used
as the default principal if container managed authentication is specified and a  <literal>
default-resource-principal</literal> is not found in the application deployment descriptors.
</para>
