<sect3><title>Properties</title>
<para>You can set properties for the <literal>mail-resource</literal> element and
then get these properties in a JavaMail <literal>Session</literal> object later. Every
property name must start with a <literal>mail-</literal> prefix. The &ProductName; changes
the dash (<literal>-</literal>) character to a period (<literal>.</literal>) in the
name of the property, then saves the property to the <literal>MailConfiguration</literal> 
and JavaMail <literal>Session</literal> objects. If the name of the property doesn&rsquo;t
start with <literal>mail-</literal>, the property is ignored.</para>
<para>For example, to define the property <literal>mail.password</literal> in a JavaMail
Session object, first edit <literal>domain.xml</literal> as follows:</para>
<programlisting>...
 &lt;mail-resource jndi-name="mail/Session" ...>
     &lt;property name="mail-password" value="adminadmin"/>
 &lt;/mail-resource>
 ...</programlisting>
<para>After getting the JavaMail <literal>Session</literal> object, get the  <literal>
mail.password</literal> property to retrieve the value <literal>adminadmin</literal>,
as follows:</para>
<programlisting>String password = session.getProperty("mail.password");</programlisting>
</sect3>
